,"Genetic mutation in collagen genes","Mucoid degeneration of connective tissue"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most common cause of ganglion cysts is \u003Cstrong\u003Emucoid degeneration of connective tissue\u003C/strong\u003E. This process involves the breakdown of connective tissue, leading to the formation of a cyst filled with a gelatinous fluid. The exact mechanism is not fully understood, but it is thought to be related to joint or tendon irritation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBacterial infection of the joint\u003C/strong\u003E - This would typically cause an infectious arthritis, not a ganglion cyst\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutoimmune inflammation of the synovium\u003C/strong\u003E - This is more characteristic of conditions like rheumatoid arthritis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGenetic mutation in collagen genes\u003C/strong\u003E - While genetic factors may play a role in some connective tissue disorders, they are not a direct cause of ganglion cysts\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect trauma to the bone\u003C/strong\u003E - Trauma can lead to other types of cysts or bone lesions, but not typically ganglion cysts\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ganglion cysts are commonly caused by mucoid degeneration of connective tissue.","Ganglion cysts are non-cancerous lumps that often develop along the tendons or joints of wrists or hands.","The exact cause of ganglion cysts is not well understood, but they are associated with joint or tendon irritation."],"references":["Gregush RE, Habusta SF. Ganglion Cyst. 2023 Jul 17. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29262133.","Dincer, F., \u0026 Samut, G. (2014). Physical examination of the hand. In Hand function: A practical guide to assessment (pp. 23-40). New York, NY: Springer New York","Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2018). Textbook of Orthopaedics, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Wojdyla, L., Hughes, T., \u0026 Stelitano, G. (2023). Hand Pathologies. In Textbook of Musculoskeletal Disorders (pp. 675-689). Cham: Springer International Publishing","Mohan, H. (2018). Textbook of pathology. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publishers"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63810"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18238"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21452"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21452","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21452"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4OIeE5BY2nmhLZTDM4qSvQsbvVhppR.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4OIeE5BY2nmhLZTDM4qSvQsbvVhppR.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":531}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63810","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63810"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-10T20:34:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-10T20:35:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10952"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78448"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null